sec.p:
Stochastic Gradient Descent (SGD) is an advanced and faster form of the conventional Gradient Descent algorithm, commonly used for tasks like classification, linear regression, and backpropagation. Its main function is to iteratively minimise the cost function from an initial starting point. The mathematical representation of SGD is provided in equation (1).
\begin{equation*}
W_{k+1}=W_{k}-\alpha \nabla L\left(W_{k}; p, q\right)
\tag{1}
\end{equation*}

It uses gradients by using an adaptive learning rate as an alternative of a hyperparameter that variates with time (Eq. (2)).
\begin{equation*}
W_{k+1}=W_{k}-\frac{\alpha}{\sqrt{M_{k+1}}+\varepsilon} \nabla L\left(W_{k}; p, q\right)
\tag{2}
\end{equation*}
Where, $M_{k+1}=\beta M_{k}+(1-\beta)\left(\nabla L\left(W_{k}; p, q\right)\right)^{2}$, $M_{k}$ is the Moving average of the squared gradient, $\beta$: Decay factor (which is close to 1)

It automatically adjusts the learning rate for each parameter according to its update history. Parameters decrease more frequently receive smaller learning rates, improving performance and eliminating the need for manual tuning. The mechanism of Adagrad is expressed in equation (3).
\begin{gather*}
W_{k+1}=W_{k}-\frac{\alpha}{\sqrt{G M_{k+1}}+\varepsilon} \nabla L\left(W_{k}; p, q\right) \\
G M_{k+1}=G M_{k}\left(\nabla L\left(W_{k}; p, q\right)\right)^{2} \\
G M_{k}: \text { Diagonal matrix elements accumulates } \\
\text { the squared gradient } \tag{3}
\end{gather*}

AdaDelta is the improved version of Adagrad that remove the necessity for a fixed initial learning rate. It adaptively updates hyper-parameters during training and is more resilient to gradient noise, using a limited window to control the impact of past accumulated gradients. Its mathematical formulation is shown in equation (4).
\begin{equation*}
W_{k+1}=W_{k}+\frac{\sqrt{E\left[\Delta m^{2}\right]_{k-1}+\varepsilon}}{\sqrt{E\left[n^{2}\right]_{k}+\varepsilon}} \nabla L\left(W_{k}; p, q\right)
\tag{4}
\end{equation*}

Adam, short for Adaptive Moment Estimation, is one of the most extensively used optimization algorithms and shares conceptual similarities with both RMSProp and Adagrad. It utilizes the L2 norm (Euclidean norm) to achieve efficient, adaptable, and fast optimization. As its name suggests, Adam estimates adaptive learning rates for individual network weights by computing the first and second moments of the gradients. The operational mechanism of the Adam optimizer is presented in equation (5).
\begin{gather*}
W_{k+1}=W_{k}-\frac{\alpha}{\sqrt{\frac{V_{k+1}}{1-\beta_{2}^{K+1}}}+\varepsilon} * \frac{U_{k+1}}{1-\beta_{1}^{K+1}} \\
\text { where }, U_{k+1}=\beta_{1} U_{k}+\left(1-\beta_{1}\right) \nabla L\left(W_{k}; p, q\right), \\
V_{k+1}=\beta_{2} V_{k}+\left(1-\beta_{2}\right)\left(\nabla L\left(W_{k}; p, q\right)\right)^{2} \tag{5}
\end{gather*}

For Adamax Equation (5) updated with $V_{k}$: exponentially weighted infinity norm of the gradients
\begin{equation*}
V_{k+1}=\max \left(\beta_{2} \cdot V_{k} \cdot\left|\nabla L\left(W_{k}; p, q\right)\right\vert\right.
\end{equation*}

Nadam, formed from the joining of Adam and Nesterov Accelerated Gradient (NAG), integrates Nesterov's momentum into Adam's adaptive moment estimation. By incorporating a look-ahead gradient update, Nadam achieves faster and more stable convergence, particularly in scenarios involving high curvature or noisy gradients. Its learning process benefits from the accelerated reduction in the moving averages of both past and current gradients. The operational formulation of the Nadam optimizer is presented in equation (6).
\begin{align*}
& W_{k+1} \\
& =W_{k}-\frac{\alpha}{\sqrt{\frac{V_{k+1}}{1-\beta_{2}^{K+1}}}+\varepsilon} \\
& *\left(\beta_{1} \frac{U_{k+1}}{1-\beta_{1}^{K+1}}+\frac{\left(1-\beta_{1}\right) \nabla L\left(W_{k}+\beta_{1} U_{k}; p, q\right)}{1-\beta_{1}^{K+1}}\right) \tag{6}
\end{align*}

In this study, DNN fully connected with four layers was designed and optimized for effective intrusion detection. The initial single-hidden-layer configuration proved inadequate, so multiple architectures were tested, and a two-hidden-layer design delivered the best results, as illustrated in Fig 2. In this fully connected network, each neuron links to every neuron in the next layer. The input vector XXX consists of 66 features $\left(\mathrm{X}=\{\mathrm{x} 1, \mathrm{x} 2, \ldots, \mathrm{x} 66\} \mathrm{X}=\backslash\left\{\mathrm{x} \_1, \mathrm{x} \_2, \ldots, \mathrm{x}_{\_}\{66\} \backslash\right\} \mathrm{X}=\{\mathrm{x} 1, \mathrm{x} 2\right.$,…, X66}), while the output vector YYY contains six values representing attack classes from (C0 to C5). The DNN architecture includes one hidden layer with 64 and another with 128 neurons, respectively, both using the ReLU [14], and a softmax output layer with six neurons. Mathematically it is expressed in equation (8).
\begin{equation*}
H L_{i}(X)=f_{\text {activation }}\left(W_{i} X+b_{i}\right)
\tag{8}
\end{equation*}

The output nodes and hidden nodes are subjected to the softmax activation function [15] and the ReLu activation function, respectively. In equations (9) and (10), the ReLu and softmax are considered.
\begin{equation*}
f_{\text {activation }(R e L u)}=\max (0, X)
\tag{9}
\end{equation*}
\begin{equation*}
f_{\text {activation (softmax) }}=\frac{e^{x_{i}}}{\sum_{k-1}^{n} e^{x_{k}}}
\tag{10}
\end{equation*}
